== Cityscape ==
[[Image:P1040733.JPG|thumb|right|Downtown Columbia, facing southeast on Fifth St.]]
[[Image:CoMoSkyline3.jpg|thumb|right|2007 skyline]]
Columbia's most commonly recognizable architectural attributes reside downtown and within the university campuses. Widely used icons of the city are the University of Missouri's [[Jesse Hall]] and the [[neo-gothic]] [[Memorial Union (University of Missouri)|Memorial Union]]. The [[David R. Francis Quadrangle]] is an example of [[Thomas Jefferson|Thomas Jefferson's]] [[Jeffersonian architecture|academic village]] concept. There are four [[historic district (United States)|historic districts]] listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] within the city: [[Downtown Columbia, Missouri|Downtown Columbia]], [[East Campus Neighborhood]], [[Francis Quadrangle]], and [[North Ninth Street Historic District]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/nrlist.htm | title=Recent Listings | work=[[National Park Service]] | accessdate=2008-01-01}}</ref> The downtown skyline is relatively low and is dominated by the 10-story [[Tiger Hotel]], and the 15-story Paquin Tower.
<!-- This image has been removed until this section grows larger in size.  [[Image:University of Missouri - Memorial Union.jpg|thumb|right|The most prominent example of [[neo-gothic architecture]] in Columbia is the [[Memorial Union (University of Missouri)|Memorial Union Tower]]]] -->
<!-- This image has been removed until this section grows larger in size.[[Image:Tiger hotel.jpg|thumb|right|Downtown Columbia]] -->

Downtown Columbia is an area of approximately one square mile surrounded by the University of Missouri on the south, Columbia College on the north, and Stephens College to the east. The area serves as Columbia's financial and business district and is the topic of a large initiative to draw tourism, which includes plans to capitalize on the area's historic architecture, and Bohemian characteristics.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.downtown.org/index.html | title=Discover The District | work=The District | accessdate=2008-01-01}}</ref> The city's historic residential core lies in a ring around downtown, extending especially to the west along Broadway, and south into the East Campus neighborhoods. Columbia can be divided into roughly 36 neighborhoods and subdivisions.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gocolumbiamo.com/Public_Comm/Neighborhood_Associations/documents/NAContactList.pdf |format=PDF| title=Columbia, Missouri Neighborhood Associations | work=City of Columbia| accessdate=2008-01-01}}</ref> The city's most dense commercial areas are primarily located along [[Interstate 70 (Missouri)|Interstate 70]], [[U.S. Route 63 (Missouri)|U.S. Route 63]], Stadium Blvd, Grindstone Pkwy, and the downtown area.

[[File:Columbia MO District Sign.JPG|thumb|Directions sign in Columbia's downtown area known as The District]]

