===2010 census===
As of the [[census]]<ref name ="FactFinder">{{cite web|title=American FactFinder|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-07-08}}</ref> of 2010, there were 108,500 people, 43,065 households, and 21,418 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|1720.0|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 46,758 housing units at an average density of {{convert|741.2|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the city was 79.0% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 11.3% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.3% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 5.2% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[Race (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 1.1% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 3.1% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 3.4% of the population.

There were 43,065 households of which 26.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 35.6% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 10.6% had a female householder with no husband present, 3.5% had a male householder with no wife present, and 50.3% were non-families. 32.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 6.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.32 and the average family size was 2.94.

In the city the population was spread out with 18.8% of residents under the age of 18; 27.3% between the ages of 18 and 24; 26.7% from 25 to 44; 18.6% from 45 to 64; and 8.5% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age in the city was 26.8 years. The gender makeup of the city was 48.3% male and 51.7% female.

===2000 census===
In 2000, the city had a day time population of 106,487.<ref name = "kabzht"/> As of the [[census]]{{GR|2}} of 2000, there were 84,531 people, 33,689 households, and 17,282 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 1,592.8 people per square mile (615.0/km²). There were 35,916 housing units at an average density of 676.8 per square mile (261.3/km²). The racial makeup of the city was 81.5% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 10.9% [[African American (U.S. Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.4% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 4.3% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], <0.1% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.8% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 2.1% from two or more races. 2.1% of the population were [[Hispanics in the United States|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race.{{GR|2}}

There were 33,689 households out of which 26.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 38.2% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 10.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 48.7% were non-families. 33.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 6.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.26 and the average family size was 2.92.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://columbiamo.areaconnect.com/statistics.htm | title=Columbia population and demographics | work=Area Connect | accessdate=2008-01-11}}</ref>

In the city the population was spread out with 19.7% under the age of 18,<ref name="demo">{{cite web | url=http://www.citytowninfo.com/places/missouri/columbia | title=Columbia, Missouri | work=City Town Info | accessdate=2008-01-11}}</ref> 26.7% from 18 to 24, 28.7% from 25 to 44, 16.2% from 45 to 64, and 8.6% who were 65 years of age or older.<ref name="demo"/> The median age was 27 years.<ref name="demo"/> For every 100 females, there were 91.8 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 89.1 males.

The median income for a household in the city was $33,729,<ref name="epo">{{cite web | url=http://www.epodunk.com/cgi-bin/incomeOverview.php?locIndex=20205 | title=Columbia, MO | work=Epodunk | accessdate=2008-01-11}}</ref> and the median income for a family was $52,288.<ref name="demo"/> Males had a median income of $34,710 versus $26,694 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $19,507.<ref name="epo"/> About 9.4% of families and 19.2% of the population were below the [[poverty line]],<ref name="demo"/> including 14.8% of those under age 18 and 5.2% of those age 65 or over. However, traditional measures of income and poverty can be misleading when applied to cities with high student populations, such as Columbia.

== Economy ==
The economy of Columbia is historically dominated by education, healthcare, and the insurance industry.<ref name = "ckbome"/> Jobs in government are also common, either in Columbia or a half-hour south in [[Jefferson City, Missouri|Jefferson City]].<ref name = "vffbdr">{{cite web | url=http://www.columbiaredi.com/area_data/LargestEmployers.php | title=Largest Employers | work=Columbia REDI | accessdate=2008-01-01}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>  Commutes into the city are also common and in 2000 the city had a day time population of 106,487.<ref name = "kabzht">{{cite web | url=http://www.missourieconomy.org/pdfs/daytime_population.pdf |format=PDF| title=Daytime Population | work=Missouri Economic Research Center | accessdate=2008-01-01}}</ref> The [[Columbia Regional Airport]] and the Missouri River [[Rocheport, Missouri|Port of Rocheport]] connect the region with trade and transportation. The University of Missouri is by far the city's largest employer.<ref name = "vffbdr"/>

The economy of the metro area is slightly larger than that of the [[Bahamas]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.missourieconomy.org/newsletter/gmp.htm | title=Economies of Missouri Metros Larger than Many Countries | work=Missouri Economic Research and Development | accessdate=2008-01-01}}</ref> With a Gross Metropolitan Product of $5.84 billion in 2004, Columbia's economy makes up 2.9% of the Gross State Product of Missouri.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://usmayors.org/metroeconomies/Top100_2006.pdf |format=PDF| title=The Role of Metro Areas in the U.S. Economy | work=U.S. Conference of Mayors |page=119 |date=March 2006 |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> Insurance corporations headquartered in Columbia include [[Shelter Insurance]], and [[Columbia Insurance Group]]. Other organizations include [[MFA Incorporated]], [[Missouri State High School Activities Association]] and [[MFA Oil]]. Companies such as [[Socket (telecommunications)|Socket]], [[Datastorm Technologies, Inc.]], [[Slackers CDs and Games]] and [[Carfax (company)|Carfax]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.consumeraffairs.com/news04/2006/10/carfax_history.html | title= Carfax History | publisher=Consumer affairs | last=McCormick | first=Lisa Wade | date=2006-10-10 | accessdate=2008-01-04}}</ref> were founded in Columbia.

MBS Textbook Exchange, regarded as the industry leader in new and used textbooks in the nation was founded in Columbia. It holds the largest inventory of new and used textbooks in the nation.

